# <YOUR_NAME> — universal operating model

This file loads in every Claude Code session on this machine. It defines
how Claude should operate across all OS folders and any standalone work.

## Memory hierarchy

Three layers of memory, queried in order at session start:

1. **Global learnings** — Graphiti, `group_id: global`. Cross-cutting
   feedback, anti-patterns, universal preferences. Applies everywhere
   regardless of which OS or project you're in.
2. **OS-level context** — Graphiti, `group_id: <os_slug>` (e.g.
   `marketing_os`, `research_os`, `engineering_os`). OS-specific
   decisions and patterns.
3. **Project-level context** — Graphiti, `group_id: <project_slug>`.
   Project-specific state.

Active OS is detected from the working directory. Active project is
detected from a `projects/<slug>/` segment in the path.

## Session start — every session, no exceptions

Before responding to the first user message:

1. Call `mcp__graphiti__search_memory_facts` with `group_ids: ["global"]`
   for cross-cutting learnings relevant to the working directory or request.
2. If inside an OS folder, also search the OS group.
3. If inside a project, also search the project group.
4. Call `mcp__graphiti__search_nodes` with the same scopes for entity context.
5. If Graphiti is unreachable, fall back to the OS folder's `MEMORY.md`
   and `session_log.md`.

Reference recent work when greeting the user ("Last session in <scope>
we were working on X — continue or start new?"). Surface only what's
relevant — don't dump everything you found.

## Universal agents (loaded automatically by Claude Code)

The following live at `~/.claude/agents/` and are invokable in every session:

- `agent-architect` — bootstraps a new project; asks framing questions
- `system-analyst` — writes specs, requirements, tickets
- `devils-advocate` — challenges assumptions, surfaces blind spots
- `discovery-agent` — surfaces unknowns and unstated assumptions
- `trend-analyst` — researches market/cultural/technical trends

Domain-specific agents live inside each OS at `<OS>/00_agents/` and are
auto-registered via `<OS>/.claude/agents/` symlinks when working inside
that OS.

## Saving learnings — what goes where

When the user corrects an approach or confirms a non-obvious one:

- **Save to `global` group** when the correction applies across domains
  (e.g. "always verify before claiming", communication-style preferences).
- **Save to `<os>` group** when the correction is OS-specific.
- **Save to `<project>` group** when scoped to a single project.

Use the `/glearn` skill to save with the right group_id. Default to the
narrowest scope that fits — promote to a wider scope only when a pattern repeats.

## Operating principles (apply everywhere)

- **Verify before claiming** — grep, read, probe before asserting how
  something works. Acknowledged uncertainty beats confident guessing.
- **One question at a time** — never present a wall of questions.
- **Fix it right, not fast** — quick patch first to unblock, then
  architectural follow-up in the same session. Don't stop at the patch.
- **Action items go in trackers, not chat asides** — file tickets for
  follow-ups rather than leaving them as conversational dangles.
- **Don't ask permission for the obvious** — if the user has set context,
  act. Reserve clarifying questions for genuine forks.

## Bootstrap commands

- `/bootstrap-os <name>` — scaffold a new OS folder under `~/Documents/<name>/`
  with the canonical structure and `.claude/` layer pre-wired.
- `/bootstrap-project <name>` — inside an OS, scaffold a new project under
  `projects/<name>/` and invoke `agent-architect`.

Both live at `~/.claude/skills/` and are available everywhere.

## File pointers

- Scripts: `~/.claude/scripts/`
- Skills: `~/.claude/skills/`
- Per-OS auto-memory: `~/.claude-work-2/projects/<encoded-os-path>/memory/`
  (created automatically by Claude Code)
